## Metal Choice for Bezel Pear Diamond Rings

The metal choice in a bezel setting carries more visual weight than in a prong setting because more metal is visible. A prong setting at six points shows metal only at those six contact points. A full bezel shows metal continuously around the entire stone perimeter. The color of that metal — and the contrast or harmony it creates with the diamond — affects the perceived diamond color and the overall aesthetic of the ring significantly.

**White gold (14K or 18K):** The most popular bezel metal for pear diamonds. White gold reflects neutral light into the stone, which does not mask color-grade deficiencies but does not introduce warm tones either. A G-color pear in a white gold bezel looks precisely like a G-color pear. White gold bezel settings at 14K provide excellent durability; 18K white gold is softer but carries more gold content. Note that white gold requires rhodium plating to maintain its appearance — replating every 18–24 months is typical for daily-wear rings.

**Yellow gold (14K or 18K):** The recommended metal for pear diamonds graded H, I, or J color. Yellow gold bezel metal reflects warm light back into the stone, masking the slight warmth of lower color grades and making them appear whiter than they actually are. A J-color pear in a yellow gold bezel can appear visually equivalent to an H-color stone in white gold — at significantly lower stone cost. Yellow gold requires no rhodium plating and is more forgiving of scratches visually (the patina development reads as character rather than wear).

**Rose gold (14K or 18K):** The warmest of the three gold alloys. Rose gold bezel settings have the same color-masking benefit as yellow gold for lower color grades, with a softer, more romantic visual character. The rose gold wall against a pear diamond creates a particularly distinctive look — the contrast between the diamond's cold white brilliance and the warm pink metal is visually striking. Most Blue Nile bezel settings are available in 14K rose gold as a standard option.

**Platinum:** The densest and most durable metal for bezel settings. Platinum is naturally white — no rhodium plating required — and its density means the bezel wall holds its shape under impact better than gold alloys. A platinum bezel is the correct specification for buyers doing active physical work or who want a ring that requires zero maintenance. The trade-off is cost: platinum bezel settings run $200–$1,200 more than equivalent 14K white gold settings at Blue Nile.

