## L/W Ratio in a Bezel Setting

The ideal length-to-width ratio for a pear diamond changes meaningfully inside a bezel setting compared to a prong setting. In prong settings, pear diamonds with L/W ratios of 1.55–1.75 are standard recommendations — the length reinforces the elongating effect while the prongs at tip and base anchor the stone without hiding it. In a full bezel, different dynamics apply.

A bezel adds visual width to the stone because the metal wall around the perimeter has its own thickness. A pear with a very long ratio (1.75+) set in a full bezel can look narrower than expected, because the metal adds horizontal mass while not adding length. The bezel wall essentially "inflates" the stone's perceived width — making very elongated pears look more proportionate and very short pears look stubby.

For **north-south bezel pear rings**, the recommended L/W range is **1.45–1.65**. This produces a visible elongating effect without the stone becoming so long that the bezel creates awkward proportions at the tip and base ends.

For **east-west bezel pear rings**, the recommended L/W range is **1.40–1.55**. In east-west orientation, the pear's width is its primary visual dimension. Too long a ratio creates a ring that looks narrow across the finger rather than wide. A 1.50 L/W pear set east-west in a full bezel reads as pleasingly oval-like across the finger — balanced, wide, and modern. Ratios above 1.60 in east-west orientation start to look like a torpedo rather than a teardrop.

For reference, how to find L/W ratio: on a GIA report, divide the "Length" measurement by the "Width" measurement in the Measurements field. A stone listed as 9.00 × 6.00 mm has an L/W ratio of 1.50. This is an ideal east-west bezel ratio and a solid north-south bezel ratio.

---

## Bezel Pear vs. Prong Pear: Which Setting Is Right for You

The bezel vs. prong decision for a pear diamond comes down to four factors: tip protection priority, light performance priority, lifestyle, and aesthetic preference. These factors rarely all point in the same direction, which is why both setting types coexist in the market rather than one eliminating the other.

**Choose a bezel set pear if:** you work with your hands, exercise wearing your ring, have children, or have a history of damaging jewelry. Choose a bezel if you have chosen a lower clarity grade and want the stone's perimeter inclusions hidden by metal. Choose a bezel if you find the east-west orientation more appealing than the vertical orientation. Choose a bezel if the minimal, modern, architectural look resonates with you more than traditional prong silhouettes.

**Choose a prong-set pear if:** light performance is your highest priority — prong settings allow light to enter from every direction, maximizing brilliance and fire. Choose prongs if you want to maximize visible face-up stone size, since prongs cover only small points at the perimeter rather than a continuous wall. Choose prongs if you prefer the traditional pear look with the elongating vertical orientation and visible tip. See the [Pear Shaped Solitaire Diamond Ring](/pear-shaped-solitaire-diamond-ring) guide for the complete prong-setting framework.

There is no objectively superior answer. Buyers who prioritize security over sparkle choose bezels. Buyers who prioritize sparkle over security choose prongs. The correct choice is the one that matches how you live in a ring.

---

## Lab-Grown Pear Diamonds in Bezel Settings

Lab-grown pear diamonds are particularly well-suited to bezel settings for one reason beyond price: lab-grown pears are available in longer, more extreme L/W ratios than natural pear diamonds without the price premium that extreme ratios command in natural stones. A natural 1ct pear with an L/W of 1.75 carries a premium because longer ratios are harder to achieve from natural rough. A lab-grown 1ct pear with L/W 1.75 carries no such premium — the ratio is determined during growth, not by a geological accident.

This matters for bezel pear buyers because east-west bezel settings benefit from ratios in the 1.45–1.60 range, which is exactly the range where lab-grown pears are plentiful, affordable, and well-cut. You are not paying extra for a specific ratio. You set your L/W filter on Blue Nile's diamond search, filter for IGI Excellent cut pears, and find stones in every ratio within your target range at consistent per-carat pricing.

For lab-grown pear diamond quality benchmarks in a bezel setting:
- **Cut:** IGI Excellent only. In a bezel, the bow-tie effect (a dark bowtie-shaped shadow across the center of the stone) is slightly more visible than in prongs because the stone is viewed through the bezel's open top rather than with side-light angles from prong gaps. Excellent cut minimizes bow-tie formation.
- **Color:** F–H. Lab-grown diamonds in F–G are essentially colorless and carry only a small premium over H. In a yellow or rose gold bezel, G–H is appropriate. In white gold or platinum, F–G.
- **Clarity:** VS2–SI1 eye-clean. Inclusions at the pear's tip and belly are hidden by the bezel metal — you can shop one clarity grade lower than you might in a prong setting and remain eye-clean. SI1 eye-clean lab pears in a full bezel are an excellent value configuration.

